of <HI>Edinburgh,</HI> therein to remain until the Lords of her Maje&s;ty's Privy-Council
<PB N="31" REF="40">
&s;hould inflict on him &s;uch furder Puni&s;hment as they &s;hould think
meet; for which Effect the &s;aids Magi&s;trates remitted his Ca&s;e to the &s;aids
Lords, as &s;aid is, conform to <HI>Interloquitor</HI> aforemention'd. In all Points,
<HI>$word$</HI> the &s;aids hail Defenders being lawfully &s;ummon'd to the &s;econd
Day of <HI>March</HI> In&s;tant, by <HI>Hendry Rankin</HI> Officer.&endq;</P>
<P>&startq;And accordingly compear'd Mr. <HI>George Graham</HI> Defender, and being
anent the Libel examin'd judicially, acknowledg'd he kept an Hou&s;e in
<HI>Edinburgh,</HI> wherein he exercis'd publick Prayers, and allow'd all to be
pre&s;ent who had a Mind to come; and that he read Prayers in the Service-Book,
where her Maje&s;ty Queen <HI>ANNE</HI>'s Name was expre&s;s'd, but
did not read her Name, neither did he pray for Her, nor kept Fa&s;ts nor
Thank&s;giving Days, except when they fell upon the praying Days, and
acknowledg'd he was not qualify'd Conform to Law by taking the Oath
of Allegiance, and &s;ub&s;cribing the &s;ame with the A&s;&s;urance to her Maje&s;ty
Q. <HI>ANNE. Sic &s;ub&s;cribitur, Mr.</HI> Grame.&endq;</P>
<P>&startq;Mr. <HI>Robert Skeen</HI> Defender pre&s;ent refus'd toan&s;wer to the Libel pre&s;ent|ly,
but craved to be allowed to &s;ee the &s;ame, and to have ane double
thereof, and ane time to an&s;wer thereto: the Magi&s;trates allow'd the
&s;ame Defender to &s;ee and an&s;wer the Libel again&s;t the morrow Morning
at Nine of the Clock, and to have an Double of the Libel for that End.&endq;</P>
<P>&startq;Mr. <HI>George Purves</HI> Defender pre&s;ent, and examin'd Anent the Libel,
Judically acknowledg'd, he kep'd a Meeting-Hon&s;e in <HI>Edinburgh,</HI> and
there preach'd and prayed; and in his Prayers he prayed for her Pre&s;ent
Maje&s;ty Queen <HI>Anne,</HI> by expre&s;&s;ing her Name; and prayed al&s;o for the
whole Royal Family; and that he was not quallifyed, Conform to Law
by taking the Oath of Allegiance, and &s;ub&s;cribing the &s;ame with the
A&s;&s;urance to her Maje&s;ty Queen <HI>Anne,</HI> and acknowledg'd he kep'd not
the Fa&s;t Day in <HI>January</HI> la&s;t, becau&s;e the re&s;t of his Brethren did not keep
it, and that he de&s;ired not to be &s;ingular, <HI>Sic &s;ub&s;eribitur, George Purves.</HI>&endq;</P>
<P>&startq;Mr. <HI>Robert Skeene</HI> Defender pre&s;ent, and examin'd Anent the Libel,
refu&s;ed to an&s;wer thereto pre&s;ently, but craved to be allow'd to &s;ee the
Libel, and to have an Double thereof, and an time to an&s;wer thereto;
The Magi&s;trates allow'd the &s;aid Defender to &s;ee and an&s;wer the Libel
again&s;t the morrow-Morning, at Nine of the Clock, and to have an
Double of the Libel for that End.&endq;</P>
<P>&startq;And the &s;aid Action being again called upon the Fourth Day of <HI>March</HI> in|&s;tant;
Mr. <HI>Robert Cheyne,</HI> and Mr. <HI>Robert Skeene</HI> Defenders, pre&s;ent, gave
in an <HI>Memorandum,</HI> containing Dilatory De&s;ences again&s;t the Libel,
which were read; and the Magi&s;trates allow'd the Defenders until <HI>Friday</HI>
next at Ten of the Clock in the Forenoon to an&s;wer the Libel.&endq;</P>
<P>&startq;And the &s;aid Action being again called upon the Fourth Day of <HI>March</HI>
in&s;tant; Mr. <HI>George Barclay</HI> Defender pre&s;ent, and examin'd Anent the
Libel, Judicially acknowledg'd, he was in u&s;e to pray for her Pre&s;ent
Maje&s;ty Queen <HI>Anne,</HI> and &s;ometimes expre&s;s'd her Name, and that he
was not quallifyed Conform to Law, by taking the Oath of Allegiance,
<PB N="32" REF="41">
and &s;ub&s;cribing the &s;ame with the A&s;&s;urance, and declared he did not
keep the Fa&s;t in <HI>January</HI> la&s;t, but that he would have keep'd the &s;ame,
if he had been de&s;ir'd &s;o to do; and being interrogate, if he would
yet qualify him&s;elf declared, that hither he had given no ground of
Jealou&s;y to the Government, and de&s;ired he might not be troubled upon
that Account, <HI>Sic &s;ub&s;$$ribitur, George Barclay.</HI>&endq;</P>
<P>&startq;Mr. <HI>David Rankin</HI> Defender, Pre&s;ent, and Examined anent the Libel,
refus'd to an&s;wer thereto, in regard, that he and &s;everal other Defen|ders
had appointed Mr. <HI>William Ab$rcrom$y</HI> Defender, to crave an delay
and an competent time to an&s;wer thereto; thereafter Defenders Pre|&s;ent.</P>
